{"event_id": "a42fde6d-1b3e-44cb-80c2-dd3b5dc267a0", "trace_id": "33fb7beac0de47af", "session_id": "a400e6eb", "timestamp": "2026-05-05T06:26:29.940936+00:00", "tool": "filesystem.write_file", "args_hash": "00fc19a2a01c4fe028629588fc2b8544c37fe1d7fdb79ef5141f67b72af75d15", "args_redacted": {"path": "workspace/ai_safety_summary.txt", "content": "AI Safety Research — 3 Most Important Recent Findings\n========================================================\n\n1. Constitutional AI (Anthropic)\n   - Approach: AI systems use self-critique and revision guided by a written\n     \"constitution\" of principles to refine their own outputs.\n   - Key Finding: Self-critique methods reduce harmful outputs by approximately\n     40% compared to standard RLHF-trained models, without requiring extensive\n     human feedback on harmful content.\n   - Significance: Demonstrates a scalable path to aligning AI behavior with\n     human values while reducing reliance on human labelers for toxic content.\n\n2. Mechanistic Interpretability (MIT & Broader Community)\n   - Approach: Reverse-engineering the internal computations of transformer\n     models by identifying interpretable \"circuits\" (sub-networks of attention\n     heads and MLP layers that perform specific functions).\n   - Key Finding: Researchers can now locate and edit specific circuits\n     responsible for factual recall, reasoning, and even refusal behavior,\n     enabling targeted modification of model behavior without retraining.\n   - Significance: Opens the door to precise safety interventions — patching\n     vulnerabilities, removing dangerous capabilities, or correcting biases at\n     the circuit level rather than through blunt retraining.\n\n3. Scalable Oversight via Debate (DeepMind / Google DeepMind)\n   - Approach: Two AI systems debate a question (one arguing for the correct\n     answer, one against) while a human judge evaluates the debate to determine\n     the truth, even when the question exceeds the judge's expertise.\n   - Key Finding: Debate protocols allow non-expert human judges to reliably\n     identify correct answers to questions beyond their own competence,\n     suggesting a viable method for supervising superhuman AI systems.\n   - Significance: Provides a theoretical and empirical foundation for\n     maintaining human control over AI systems that may eventually surpass\n     human capabilities in critical domains.\n\n---\nCompiled from recent AI safety literature (2024–2025).\n"}, "input_labels": {"SI": "SI:LOW", "DS": "DS:NORMAL"}, "policy_decision": "ALLOW", "matched_rule": "", "rule_reason": "No defense baseline — PEP bypassed", "prev_event_hash": "d31d11047242e99dd8f3344cfade82602ed39b56515a36d31c7eabef60f0c863", "event_hash": "a2970099f383cbebc083fb741c0596fa34c69d9371a31eb2ab5b6a64b3c575d4"}
